<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-solving-simultaneous-equations-graphically" original="PRECALC/modules/m49420/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
  <title>Solving Simultaneous Equations Graphically</title>

  <!-- Content summary: - Illustrate how to solve a linear equation (straight line) and a non-linear equation (parabola or cubic), using examples. - Accurately plotting both functions on the same grid and identifying the coordinates (x, y) of their intersection points. -->

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Solve simultaneous equations of a linear and a quadratic and cubic equations graphically</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <!-- BEGIN BORROWED CONTENT -->

<!-- Borrowed from PRECALC fs-id1165134573832: Solving Systems of Equations by Graphing -->
  
  <p>There are multiple methods of solving systems of linear equations. For a <term>system of linear equations</term> in two variables, we can determine both the type of system and the solution by graphing the system of equations on the same set of axes.</p>
  
  <example xml:id="PRECALC-VJvVuaFbKo" original="PRECALC/modules/m49420/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Solving a System of Equations in Two Variables by Graphing</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Solve the following system of equations by graphing. Identify the type of system.</p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>2x+y=−8</mrow>
            <mrow>x-y=−1</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Solve the first equation for <m>y.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>2x+y=−8</mrow>
            <mrow>y=−2x−8</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>Solve the second equation for <m>y.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>x-y=−1</mrow>
            <mrow>y=x+1</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>Graph both equations on the same set of axes as in <xref ref="PRECALC-mn8ycAqsWd" />.</p>
        <figure xml:id="PRECALC-mn8ycAqsWd" original="PRECALC/modules/m49420/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <caption>This image displays a Cartesian coordinate system with grid lines, an x-axis, and a y-axis. Two linear equations are plotted. The first line is red and labeled "y = x + 1". The second line is blue and labeled "y = -2x - 8". The two lines intersect at a single point, which is marked with a black dot and explicitly labeled with the coordinates "(-3, -2)".</caption>
          <image source="PRECALC/CNX_Precalc_Figure_09_01_012.jpg" width="80%" />
        </figure>
        <p>The lines appear to intersect at the point <m>(−3,−2).</m> We can check to make sure that this is the solution to the system by substituting the ordered pair into both equations.</p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>2(−3)+(−2)=−8</mrow>
            <mrow>−8=−8 &amp; \text{ True }</mrow>
            <mrow>(−3)-(−2)=−1</mrow>
            <mrow>−1=−1 &amp; \text{ True }</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>The solution to the system is the ordered pair <m>(−3,−2),</m> so the system is independent.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  
  <insight xml:id="PRECALC-Cnizk4s82c" original="PRECALC/modules/m49420/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>
        <em>Can graphing be used if the system is inconsistent or dependent?</em>
      </title>
      <p>
        <em>Yes, in both cases we can still graph the system to determine the type of system and solution. If the two lines are parallel, the system has no solution and is inconsistent. If the two lines are identical, the system has infinite solutions and is a dependent system.</em>
      </p>
    </insight>
  
  <convention>
      <p>This section <xref ref="sec-solving-simultaneous-equations-graphically" text="title"/> is adapted from "<url href="https://github.com/openstax/osbooks-college-algebra-bundle/tree/e10e6b91143fe884c7c60dc0ad82ef23e1be0aa5/modules/m49420/index.cnxml">Solving Systems of Equations by Graphing</url>" in Open STAX Precalculus 2e, used under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/deed.en">CC-BY-4.0</url>.</p>
    </convention>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->
</section>
